# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: segment-routing
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:segment-routing/forwarding-information-base] A **forwarding information base** (**FIB**), also known as a **forwarding table** or **MAC** (**address**) **table**, is most commonly used in network bridging, routing, and similar functions to find the proper output network interface controller to which the input interface should forward a packet.
[src:segment-routing/forwarding-information-base] It is a dynamic table that maps MAC addresses to ports.
[src:segment-routing/forwarding-information-base] It is the essential mechanism that separates network switches from Ethernet hubs.
[src:segment-routing/forwarding-information-base] Content-addressable memory (CAM) is typically used to efficiently implement the FIB, thus it is sometimes called a **CAM table**.
[src:segment-routing/forwarding-information-base] At the data link layer, a FIB is most notably used to facilitate Ethernet bridging based on MAC addresses.
[src:segment-routing/forwarding-information-base] Other data-link-layer technologies using FIBs include Frame Relay, Asynchronous Transfer Mode (ATM) and Multiprotocol Label Switching (MPLS).
[src:segment-routing/forwarding-information-base] The role of an Ethernet switch is to forward Ethernet frames from one port to another.
[src:segment-routing/forwarding-information-base] The presence of a FIB is one attribute that separates a switch from a hub.
[src:segment-routing/forwarding-information-base] Without a functional FIB, all frames received by a network switch would be echoed back out to all other ports, much like an Ethernet hub.
[src:segment-routing/forwarding-information-base] Switches learn the port on which they first saw a particular source address and associate that port with that address.
[src:segment-routing/forwarding-information-base] When the bridge subsequently receives a frame with a destination address in its FIB, it sends the frame out the port stored in the FIB entry.
[src:segment-routing/forwarding-information-base] The FIB is a memory construct used by Ethernet switch to map a station's MAC address to the switch port the station is connected to.
[src:segment-routing/forwarding-information-base] This allows switches to facilitate communications between connected stations at high speed.
[src:segment-routing/forwarding-information-base] While the exact mechanics of a forwarding table is implementation-specific, the general model for Frame Relay is that switches have statically defined forwarding tables, one per interface.
[src:segment-routing/forwarding-information-base] When a frame with a given data link connection identifier (DLCI) is received on one interface, the table associated with that interface gives the outgoing interface, and the new DLCI to insert into the frame's address field.
[src:segment-routing/forwarding-information-base] ATM switches have link-level forwarding tables much like those used in Frame Relay.
[src:segment-routing/forwarding-information-base] Rather than a DLCI, however, interfaces have forwarding tables that specify the outgoing interface by *virtual path identifier* (VPI) and *virtual circuit identifier* (VCI).
[src:segment-routing/forwarding-information-base] These tables may be configured statically, or they can be distributed by the Private Network-to-Network Interface (PNNI) protocol.
[src:segment-routing/forwarding-information-base] When PNNI is in use, the ATM switches at the edges of the network map one of the standard ATM end-to-end identifiers, such as an NSAP address, to the next-hop VPI/VCI.
[src:segment-routing/forwarding-information-base] MPLS has many similarities, at the forwarding level, to ATM.
[src:segment-routing/forwarding-information-base] The label edge routers at the edges of an MPLS cloud map between the end-to-end identifier, such as an IP address, and a link-local label.
[src:segment-routing/forwarding-information-base] At each MPLS hop, there is a forwarding table that tells the label-switched router which outgoing interface is to receive the MPLS packet, and what label to use when sending the packet out that interface.
[src:segment-routing/forwarding-information-base] Network layer addresses, such as IP addresses, are used on different types of media and can be handled similarly in all cases.
[src:segment-routing/forwarding-information-base] FIBs are optimized for fast lookup of destination addresses and can improve performance of forwarding compared to using the routing information base (RIB) directly.
[src:segment-routing/forwarding-information-base] The RIB is optimized for efficient updating by routing protocols and other control plane methods, and contain the full set of routes learned by the router.
[src:segment-routing/forwarding-information-base] Earlier implementations cached only a subset of the routes most frequently used in actual forwarding, and this worked reasonably well for enterprises where there is a meaningful most-frequently-used subset.
[src:segment-routing/forwarding-information-base] Routers used for accessing the entire Internet, however, experienced severe performance degradation in refreshing routes cached in a small FIB, and various implementations moved to having FIBs in one-to-one correspondence with the RIB.
[src:segment-routing/forwarding-information-base] FIBs can also play a role in an Internet best current practice (BCP) of ingress filtering.
[src:segment-routing/forwarding-information-base] While the IETF document BCP 38 on ingress filtering does not specify a method of implementing source address filtering, some router vendors have implemented a mechanism that employs reverse-path forwarding lookups in the router's tables to perform this check.
[src:segment-routing/forwarding-information-base] This is often implemented as a lookup in the FIB of the *source* address of the packet.
[src:segment-routing/forwarding-information-base] If the interface has no route to the source address, the packet is assumed to be part of a denial of service attack, using a spoofed source address, and the router discards the packet.
[src:segment-routing/forwarding-information-base] When the router is multihomed, ingress filtering becomes more complex.
[src:segment-routing/forwarding-information-base] There are perfectly reasonable operational scenarios in which a packet could arrive on one interface, but that specific interface might not have a route to the source address.
[src:segment-routing/forwarding-information-base] For the routers near the edge of the Internet, packet filters can provide a simpler and more effective solution than methods that employ routing information lookup, though this approach can be challenging when managing routers that are reconfigured often.
[src:segment-routing/forwarding-information-base] Ingress filtering for multihomed routers will accept the packet if there is a route back to its source address from *any* interface on the router.
[src:segment-routing/forwarding-information-base] For this type of filtering, the router may also maintain an *adjacency table*, also organized for fast lookup, that keeps track of the router interface addresses that are on all directly connected routers.
[src:segment-routing/forwarding-information-base] Differentiated services provides an additional method to select outgoing interfaces, based on a field that indicates the forwarding priority of the packet, as well as the preference of the packet to be dropped in the presence of congestion.
[src:segment-routing/forwarding-information-base] Routers that support differentiated service not only have to look up the output interface for the destination address, but need to send the packet to the interface that best matches the differentiated services requirements.
[src:segment-routing/forwarding-information-base] In other words, as well as matching the destination address, the FIB has to match differentiated services code points (DSCP).
[src:segment-routing/forwarding-information-base] Specific router implementations may, when a destination address or other FIB criterion is matched, specify another action to be done before forwarding (e.g., accounting or encryption), or apply an access control list that may cause the packet to be dropped.
[src:segment-routing/forwarding-information-base] CAM tables can be targeted for setting up a man-in-the-middle attack.
[src:segment-routing/forwarding-information-base] A threat agent which has control of a device connected to an Ethernet switch can use MAC flooding to attack the switch's CAM table.
[src:segment-routing/forwarding-information-base] If the table fills up, other traffic is treated as broadcast, unknown-unicast and multicast traffic and is forwarded to all ports making it available to the attacker.
[src:segment-routing/ip-routing] Networks are separated from each other by specialized hosts, called gateways or routers with specialized software support optimized for routing.
[src:segment-routing/ip-routing] **IP forwarding** algorithms in most routing software determine a route through a shortest path algorithm.
[src:segment-routing/ip-routing] In routers, packets arriving at an interface are examined for source and destination addressing and queued to the appropriate outgoing interface according to their destination address and a set of rules and performance metrics.
[src:segment-routing/ip-routing] Rules are encoded in a routing table that contains entries for all interfaces and their connected networks.
[src:segment-routing/ip-routing] If no rule satisfies the requirements for a network packet, it is forwarded to a default route.
[src:segment-routing/ip-routing] Routing tables are maintained either manually by a network administrator, or updated dynamically by a routing protocol.
[src:segment-routing/ip-routing] A routing protocol specifies how routers communicate and share information about the topology of the network, and the capabilities of each routing node.
[src:segment-routing/ip-routing] Different protocols are often used for different topologies or different application areas.
[src:segment-routing/ip-routing] For example, the Open Shortest Path First (OSPF) protocol is generally used within an enterprise and the Border Gateway Protocol (BGP) is used on a global scale.
[src:segment-routing/ip-routing] BGP is the de facto standard for worldwide Internet routing.
[src:segment-routing/ip-routing] Routing protocols may be broadly distinguished by their realm of operation in terms of network scope.
[src:segment-routing/ip-routing] Interior gateway protocols are used for routing within autonomous systems, while exterior gateway protocols route traffic between them.
[src:segment-routing/ip-routing] The former group is exemplified by the Routing Information Protocol (RIP) and Open Shortest Path First (OSPF), while the Exterior Gateway Protocol (EGP) and the Border Gateway Protocol (BGP) are examples of the exterior type.
[src:segment-routing/ip-routing] BGP is the dominant route distribution protocol used on the Internet.
[src:segment-routing/ip-routing] The IP forwarding algorithm is a specific implementation of routing for IP networks.
[src:segment-routing/ip-routing] In order to achieve a successful transfer of data, the algorithm uses a routing table to select a next-hop router as the next destination for a datagram.
[src:segment-routing/ip-routing] When multiple route table entries match, the entry with the longest subnet mask is chosen as it is the most specific one.
[src:segment-routing/ip-routing] If there are multiple routes with the same subnet mask, the route with the lowest metric is used.
[src:segment-routing/ip-routing] If there are multiple default routes, the metric is also used to determine which to use.
[src:segment-routing/ip-routing] If there are multiple routes with the same subnet mask and metric, the system may use equal-cost multi-path routing as a forwarding strategy.
[src:segment-routing/ip-routing] When no route is available, an ICMP error message is sent to the originator of the packet, to inform that host that the packet could not be delivered.
[src:segment-routing/ip-routing] To avoid unnecessary retransmission to avoid network congestion, the sending host should either stop transmitting or choose another address or route.
[src:segment-routing/ip-routing] The host has several network interfaces.
[src:segment-routing/ip-routing] *eth0* is the interface name of the network interface card representing an Ethernet port.
[src:segment-routing/ip-routing] *ppp0* is a PPPoE interface, which is configured as the default route in this example.
[src:segment-routing/ip-routing] A default route is recognized by the destination *0.0.0.0* and the flag *G*.
[src:segment-routing/ip-routing] A network router is identified by the network mask *255.255.255.255* and the flag *H*.
[src:segment-routing/label-switching] Each packet is assigned a label number and the switching takes place after examination of the label assigned to each packet.
[src:segment-routing/label-switching] The switching is much faster than IP-routing.
[src:segment-routing/label-switching] New technologies such as Multiprotocol Label Switching (MPLS) use label switching.
[src:segment-routing/label-switching] The established ATM protocol also uses label switching at its core.
[src:segment-routing/label-switching] "Examples of the label switching (or virtual circuit) model include Frame Relay, ATM, and MPLS.
[src:segment-routing/label-switching] (QoS) state is established for traffic streams on each hop along a network path.
[src:segment-routing/label-switching] A related topic is multilayer switching, which discusses silicon-based wire-speed routing devices that examine not only network-layer packet information but also layer 4 (transport) and layer-7 (application) information.
[src:segment-routing/multiprotocol-label-switching] MPLS was originally developed to improve packet forwarding by reducing the reliance on complex routing table lookups.
[src:segment-routing/multiprotocol-label-switching] With the introduction of hardware-based forwarding engines, forwarding speed is no longer the main reason for deployment, and MPLS today is more often used for traffic engineering, differentiated services quality of service, and BGP/MPLS IP virtual private networks (VPNs).
[src:segment-routing/multiprotocol-label-switching] In an MPLS network, packet-forwarding decisions are made solely on the contents of labels, without the need to examine the packet itself.
[src:segment-routing/multiprotocol-label-switching] This allows for the creation of end-to-end connections across any type of transport medium, using any protocol.
[src:segment-routing/multiprotocol-label-switching] The primary benefit is to eliminate dependence on a particular OSI data link layer technology, and eliminate the need for multiple layer-2 networks to satisfy different types of traffic.
[src:segment-routing/multiprotocol-label-switching] Multiprotocol label switching belongs to the family of packet-switched networks.
[src:segment-routing/multiprotocol-label-switching] MPLS operates at a layer between traditional definitions of OSI Layer 2 (data link layer) and Layer 3 (network layer), and is often referred to as a *layer 2.5* protocol.
[src:segment-routing/multiprotocol-label-switching] It was designed to provide a unified data-carrying service for both circuit-based clients and packet-switching clients which provide a datagram service model.
[src:segment-routing/multiprotocol-label-switching] It can be used to carry many different kinds of traffic, including IP packets, as well as native Asynchronous Transfer Mode (ATM), Frame Relay, Synchronous Optical Networking (SONET) or Ethernet.
[src:segment-routing/multiprotocol-label-switching] MPLS can exist in both an IPv4 and an IPv6 environment, using appropriate routing protocols.
[src:segment-routing/multiprotocol-label-switching] The major goal of MPLS development was the increase of routing speed.
[src:segment-routing/multiprotocol-label-switching] This goal is no longer relevant because of the usage of newer switching methods such as ASIC, TCAM and CAM-based switching able to forward plain IPv4 as fast as MPLS labeled packets.
[src:segment-routing/multiprotocol-label-switching] Now, therefore, the main benefit of MPLS is to implement limited traffic engineering and layer 3 or layer 2 service provider type VPNs over IPv4 networks.
[src:segment-routing/multiprotocol-label-switching] MPLS is standardized by the IETF in RFC 3031.
[src:segment-routing/multiprotocol-label-switching] It is deployed to connect as few as two facilities to very large deployments.
[src:segment-routing/multiprotocol-label-switching] In practice, MPLS is mainly used to forward IP protocol data units and Virtual Private LAN Service (VPLS) Ethernet traffic.
[src:segment-routing/multiprotocol-label-switching] Major applications of MPLS are telecommunications traffic engineering and MPLS VPN.
[src:segment-routing/multiprotocol-label-switching] In 1996 a group from Ipsilon Networks proposed a *flow management protocol*.
[src:segment-routing/multiprotocol-label-switching] Their *IP Switching* technology, which was defined only to work over ATM, did not achieve market dominance.
[src:segment-routing/multiprotocol-label-switching] Cisco Systems introduced a related proposal, not restricted to ATM transmission, called *Tag Switching* with its Tag Distribution Protocol (TDP).
[src:segment-routing/multiprotocol-label-switching] It was a Cisco proprietary proposal, and was renamed *Label Switching*.
[src:segment-routing/multiprotocol-label-switching] It was handed over to the Internet Engineering Task Force (IETF) for open standardization.
[src:segment-routing/multiprotocol-label-switching] The IETF formed the MPLS Working Group in 1997.
[src:segment-routing/multiprotocol-label-switching] Work involved proposals from other vendors, and development of a consensus protocol that combined features from several vendors' work.
[src:segment-routing/multiprotocol-label-switching] Some time later it was recognized that the work on threaded indices by Girish Chandranmenon and George Varghese had invented the idea of using labels to represent destination prefixes that was central to tag switching.
[src:segment-routing/multiprotocol-label-switching] One original motivation was to allow the creation of simple high-speed switches since for a significant length of time it was considered impractical to forward IP packets entirely in hardware.
[src:segment-routing/multiprotocol-label-switching] Advances in VLSI and in forwarding algorithms have made hardware forwarding of IP packets possible and common.
[src:segment-routing/multiprotocol-label-switching] The current advantages of MPLS primarily revolve around the ability to support multiple service models and perform traffic management.
[src:segment-routing/multiprotocol-label-switching] MPLS also offers a robust recovery framework that goes beyond the simple protection rings of synchronous optical networking (SONET/SDH).
[src:segment-routing/multiprotocol-label-switching] A number of different technologies were previously deployed with essentially identical goals, such as Frame Relay and ATM.
[src:segment-routing/multiprotocol-label-switching] Frame Relay and ATM use *labels* to move frames or cells through a network.
[src:segment-routing/multiprotocol-label-switching] The header of the Frame Relay frame and the ATM cell refers to the virtual circuit that the frame or cell resides on.
[src:segment-routing/multiprotocol-label-switching] The similarity between Frame Relay, ATM, and MPLS is that at each hop throughout the network, the *label* value in the header is changed.
[src:segment-routing/multiprotocol-label-switching] This is different from the forwarding of IP packets.
[src:segment-routing/multiprotocol-label-switching] MPLS technologies have evolved with the strengths and weaknesses of ATM in mind.
[src:segment-routing/multiprotocol-label-switching] MPLS is designed to have lower overhead than ATM while providing connection-oriented services for variable-length frames, and has replaced much use of ATM in the market.
[src:segment-routing/multiprotocol-label-switching] MPLS dispenses with the cell-switching and signaling-protocol baggage of ATM.
[src:segment-routing/multiprotocol-label-switching] MPLS recognizes that small ATM cells are not needed in the core of modern networks, since modern optical networks are fast enough that even full-length 1500-byte packets do not incur significant real-time queuing delays.
[src:segment-routing/multiprotocol-label-switching] At the same time, MPLS attempts to preserve the traffic engineering (TE) and out-of-band control that made Frame Relay and ATM attractive for deploying large-scale networks.
[src:segment-routing/multiprotocol-label-switching] MPLS works by prefixing packets with an MPLS header, containing one or more labels.
[src:segment-routing/multiprotocol-label-switching] Prior to 2009 this field was called EXP.
[src:segment-routing/multiprotocol-label-switching] If this flag is set, it signifies that the current label is the last in the stack.
[src:segment-routing/multiprotocol-label-switching] These MPLS-labeled packets are switched based on the label instead of a lookup in the IP routing table.
[src:segment-routing/multiprotocol-label-switching] When MPLS was conceived, label switching was faster than a routing table lookup because switching could take place directly within the switched fabric and avoided CPU and software involvement.
[src:segment-routing/multiprotocol-label-switching] The presence of such a label has to be indicated to the switch.
[src:segment-routing/multiprotocol-label-switching] In the case of Ethernet frames this is done through the use of EtherType values 0x8847 and 0x8848, for unicast and multicast connections respectively.
[src:segment-routing/multiprotocol-label-switching] An MPLS router that performs routing based only on the label is called a **label switch router** (**LSR**) or **transit router**.
[src:segment-routing/multiprotocol-label-switching] This is a type of router located in the middle of an MPLS network.
[src:segment-routing/multiprotocol-label-switching] It is responsible for switching the labels used to route packets.
[src:segment-routing/multiprotocol-label-switching] When an LSR receives a packet, it uses the label included in the packet header as an index to determine the next hop on the label-switched path (LSP) and a corresponding label for the packet from a Label Information Base.
[src:segment-routing/multiprotocol-label-switching] The old label is then removed from the header and replaced with the new label before the packet is routed forward.
[src:segment-routing/multiprotocol-label-switching] A **label edge router** (LER, also **edge LSR** (which is "technically more correct") or simply *edge router*) is a router that operates at the edge of an MPLS network and acts as the entry and exit points for the network.
[src:segment-routing/multiprotocol-label-switching] LERs *push* an MPLS label onto an incoming packet and *pop* it off an outgoing packet.
[src:segment-routing/multiprotocol-label-switching] Alternatively, under penultimate hop popping this function may instead be performed by the LSR directly connected to the LER.
[src:segment-routing/multiprotocol-label-switching] When forwarding an IP datagram into the MPLS domain, a LER uses routing information to determine the appropriate label to be affixed, labels the packet accordingly, and then forwards the labeled packet into the MPLS domain.
[src:segment-routing/multiprotocol-label-switching] Likewise, upon receiving a labeled packet that is destined to exit the MPLS domain, the LER strips off the label and forwards the resulting IP packet using normal IP forwarding rules.
[src:segment-routing/multiprotocol-label-switching] In the specific context of an MPLS-based virtual private network (VPN), LERs that function as ingress or egress routers to the VPN are often called provider edge (PE) routers.
[src:segment-routing/multiprotocol-label-switching] Devices that function only as transit routers are similarly called provider (P) routers.
[src:segment-routing/multiprotocol-label-switching] The job of a P router is significantly easier than that of a PE router.
[src:segment-routing/multiprotocol-label-switching] Labels may be distributed between LERs and LSRs using the Label Distribution Protocol (LDP) or Resource Reservation Protocol (RSVP).
[src:segment-routing/multiprotocol-label-switching] LSRs in an MPLS network regularly exchange label and reachability information with each other using standardized procedures in order to build a complete picture of the network so that they can then use that information to forward the packets.
[src:segment-routing/multiprotocol-label-switching] Label-switched paths (LSPs) are established by the network operator for a variety of purposes, such as to create network-based IP virtual private networks or to route traffic along specified paths through the network.
[src:segment-routing/multiprotocol-label-switching] In many respects, LSPs are not different from permanent virtual circuits (PVCs) in ATM or Frame Relay networks, except that they are not dependent on a particular layer-2 technology.
[src:segment-routing/multiprotocol-label-switching] When an unlabeled packet enters the ingress router and needs to be passed on to an MPLS tunnel, the router first determines the forwarding equivalence class (FEC) for the packet and then inserts one or more labels in the packet's newly created MPLS header.
[src:segment-routing/multiprotocol-label-switching] The packet is then passed on to the next hop router for this tunnel.
[src:segment-routing/multiprotocol-label-switching] From an OSI model perspective, the MPLS Header is added between the network layer header and link layer header.
[src:segment-routing/multiprotocol-label-switching] When a labeled packet is received by an MPLS router, the topmost label is examined.
[src:segment-routing/multiprotocol-label-switching] Based on the contents of the label a *swap*, *push* or *pop* operation is performed on the packet's label stack.
[src:segment-routing/multiprotocol-label-switching] Routers can have prebuilt lookup tables that tell them which kind of operation to do based on the topmost label of the incoming packet so they can process the packet very quickly.
[src:segment-routing/multiprotocol-label-switching] During these operations, the contents of the packet below the MPLS Label stack are not examined.
[src:segment-routing/multiprotocol-label-switching] Indeed, transit routers typically need only to examine the topmost label on the stack.
[src:segment-routing/multiprotocol-label-switching] The forwarding of the packet is done based on the contents of the labels, which allows protocol-independent packet forwarding that does not need to look at a protocol-dependent routing table and avoids the expensive IP longest prefix match at each hop.
[src:segment-routing/multiprotocol-label-switching] At the egress router, when the last label has been popped, only the payload remains.
[src:segment-routing/multiprotocol-label-switching] This can be an IP packet or any type of packet.
[src:segment-routing/multiprotocol-label-switching] The egress router must, therefore, have routing information for the packet's payload since it must forward it without the help of label lookup tables.
[src:segment-routing/multiprotocol-label-switching] An MPLS transit router has no such requirement.
[src:segment-routing/multiprotocol-label-switching] Usually, the last label is popped off at the penultimate hop (the hop before the egress router).
[src:segment-routing/multiprotocol-label-switching] This is called penultimate hop popping (PHP).
[src:segment-routing/multiprotocol-label-switching] This is useful in cases where the egress router has many packets leaving MPLS tunnels and thus spends significant CPU resources on these transitions.
[src:segment-routing/multiprotocol-label-switching] By using PHP, transit routers connected directly to this egress router effectively offload it, by popping the last label themselves.
[src:segment-routing/multiprotocol-label-switching] In the label distribution protocols, this PHP label pop action is advertised as label value 3 (implicit null) and is never found in a label, since it means that the label is to be popped.
[src:segment-routing/multiprotocol-label-switching] Several MPLS services including end-to-end QoS management, and 6PE, require keeping a label even between the penultimate and the last MPLS router, with a label disposition always done on the last MPLS router, ultimate hop popping (UHP).
[src:segment-routing/multiprotocol-label-switching] Some specific label values have been notably reserved for this use.
[src:segment-routing/multiprotocol-label-switching] An MPLS header does not identify the type of data carried inside the MPLS path.
[src:segment-routing/multiprotocol-label-switching] To carry two different types of traffic between the same two routers, with different treatment by the core routers for each type, a separate MPLS path for each type of traffic is required.
[src:segment-routing/multiprotocol-label-switching] A label-switched path (LSP) is a path through an MPLS network set up by the NMS or by a signaling protocol such as LDP, RSVP-TE, BGP (or the now deprecated CR-LDP).
[src:segment-routing/multiprotocol-label-switching] The path is set up based on criteria in the FEC.
[src:segment-routing/multiprotocol-label-switching] The path begins at an LER, which makes a decision on which label to prefix to a packet based on the appropriate FEC.
[src:segment-routing/multiprotocol-label-switching] It then forwards the packet along to the next router in the path, which swaps the packet's outer label for another label, and forwards it to the next router.
[src:segment-routing/multiprotocol-label-switching] The last router in the path removes the label from the packet and forwards the packet based on the header of its next layer, for example IPv4.
[src:segment-routing/multiprotocol-label-switching] Due to the forwarding of packets through an LSP being opaque to higher network layers, an LSP is also sometimes referred to as an MPLS tunnel.
[src:segment-routing/multiprotocol-label-switching] The router which first prefixes the MPLS header to a packet is an ingress router.
[src:segment-routing/multiprotocol-label-switching] The last router in an LSP, which pops the label from the packet, is called an egress router.
[src:segment-routing/multiprotocol-label-switching] Routers in between, which need only swap labels, are called transit routers or label switch routers (LSRs).
[src:segment-routing/multiprotocol-label-switching] Note that LSPs are unidirectional; they enable a packet to be label switched through the MPLS network from one endpoint to another.
[src:segment-routing/multiprotocol-label-switching] Since bidirectional communication is typically desired, the aforementioned dynamic signaling protocols can automatically set up a separate LSP in the opposite direction.
[src:segment-routing/multiprotocol-label-switching] When link protection is considered, LSPs can be categorized as primary (working), secondary (backup) and tertiary (LSP of last resort).
[src:segment-routing/multiprotocol-label-switching] There are two standardized protocols for managing MPLS paths: the Label Distribution Protocol (LDP) and RSVP-TE, an extension of the Resource Reservation Protocol (RSVP) for traffic engineering.
[src:segment-routing/multiprotocol-label-switching] Furthermore, there exist extensions of the Border Gateway Protocol (BGP) that can be used to manage an MPLS path.
[src:segment-routing/multiprotocol-label-switching] Multicast was, for the most part, an afterthought in MPLS design.
[src:segment-routing/multiprotocol-label-switching] It was introduced by point-to-multipoint RSVP-TE.
[src:segment-routing/multiprotocol-label-switching] It was driven by service provider requirements to transport broadband video over MPLS.
[src:segment-routing/multiprotocol-label-switching] The hub and spoke multipoint LSP (HSMP LSP) was also introduced by IETF.
[src:segment-routing/multiprotocol-label-switching] HSMP LSP is mainly used for multicast, time synchronization, and other purposes.
[src:segment-routing/multiprotocol-label-switching] MPLS works in conjunction with the Internet Protocol (IP) and its routing protocols, usually interior gateway protocols (IGPs).
[src:segment-routing/multiprotocol-label-switching] MPLS-capable devices are referred to as LSRs.
[src:segment-routing/multiprotocol-label-switching] The paths an LSR knows can be defined using explicit hop-by-hop configuration, or are dynamically routed by the Constrained Shortest Path First (CSPF) algorithm, or are configured as a loose route that avoids a particular IP address or that is partly explicit and partly dynamic.
[src:segment-routing/multiprotocol-label-switching] In a pure IP network, the shortest path to a destination is chosen even when the path becomes congested.
[src:segment-routing/multiprotocol-label-switching] Meanwhile, in an IP network with MPLS Traffic Engineering CSPF routing, constraints such as the RSVP bandwidth of the traversed links can also be considered, such that the shortest path with available bandwidth will be chosen.
[src:segment-routing/multiprotocol-label-switching] MPLS Traffic Engineering relies upon the use of TE extensions to Open Shortest Path First (OSPF) or Intermediate System to Intermediate System (IS-IS) and RSVP.
[src:segment-routing/multiprotocol-label-switching] In addition to the constraint of RSVP bandwidth, users can also define their own constraints by specifying link attributes and special requirements for tunnels to route (or not to route) over links with certain attributes.
[src:segment-routing/multiprotocol-label-switching] In the event of a network element failure when recovery mechanisms are employed at the IP layer, restoration may take several seconds which may be unacceptable for real-time applications such as VoIP.
[src:segment-routing/multiprotocol-label-switching] In contrast, MPLS local protection meets the requirements of real-time applications with recovery times comparable to those of shortest path bridging networks or SONET rings of less than 50 ms.
[src:segment-routing/multiprotocol-label-switching] MPLS can make use of existing ATM network or Frame Relay infrastructure, as its labeled flows can be mapped to ATM or Frame Relay virtual-circuit identifiers, and vice versa.
[src:segment-routing/multiprotocol-label-switching] Frame Relay aimed to make more efficient use of existing physical resources, which allow for the underprovisioning of data services by telecommunications companies (telcos) to their customers, as clients were unlikely to be utilizing a data service 100 percent of the time.
[src:segment-routing/multiprotocol-label-switching] Consequently, oversubscription of capacity by the telcos, while financially advantageous to the provider, can directly affect overall performance.
[src:segment-routing/multiprotocol-label-switching] Telcos often sold Frame Relay to businesses looking for a cheaper alternative to dedicated lines; its use in different geographic areas depended greatly on governmental and telecommunication companies' policies.
[src:segment-routing/multiprotocol-label-switching] Many customers migrated from Frame Relay to MPLS over IP or Ethernet, which in many cases reduced costs and improved manageability and performance of their wide area networks.
[src:segment-routing/multiprotocol-label-switching] While the underlying protocols and technologies are different, both MPLS and ATM provide a connection-oriented service for transporting data across computer networks.
[src:segment-routing/multiprotocol-label-switching] In both technologies, connections are signaled between endpoints, the connection state is maintained at each node in the path, and encapsulation techniques are used to carry data across the connection.
[src:segment-routing/multiprotocol-label-switching] Excluding differences in the signaling protocols (RSVP/LDP for MPLS and PNNI for ATM) there still remain significant differences in the behavior of the technologies.
[src:segment-routing/multiprotocol-label-switching] The most significant difference is in the transport and encapsulation methods.
[src:segment-routing/multiprotocol-label-switching] MPLS is able to work with variable-length packets while ATM uses fixed-length (53 bytes) cells.
[src:segment-routing/multiprotocol-label-switching] Packets must be segmented, transported and re-assembled over an ATM network using an adaptation layer, which adds significant complexity and overhead to the data stream.
[src:segment-routing/multiprotocol-label-switching] MPLS, on the other hand, simply adds a label to the head of each packet and transmits it on the network.
[src:segment-routing/multiprotocol-label-switching] Differences exist, as well, in the nature of the connections.
[src:segment-routing/multiprotocol-label-switching] An MPLS connection (LSP) is unidirectional, allowing data to flow in only one direction between two endpoints.
[src:segment-routing/multiprotocol-label-switching] Establishing two-way communications between endpoints requires a pair of LSPs be established.
[src:segment-routing/multiprotocol-label-switching] Because two LSPs are used, data flowing in the forward direction may use a different path from data flowing in the reverse direction.
[src:segment-routing/multiprotocol-label-switching] ATM point-to-point connections (virtual circuits), on the other hand, are bidirectional, allowing data to flow in both directions over the same path.
[src:segment-routing/multiprotocol-label-switching] Both ATM and MPLS support tunneling of connections inside connections.
[src:segment-routing/multiprotocol-label-switching] MPLS uses label stacking to accomplish this while ATM uses *virtual paths*.
[src:segment-routing/multiprotocol-label-switching] MPLS can stack multiple labels to form tunnels within tunnels.
[src:segment-routing/multiprotocol-label-switching] The ATM virtual path indicator (VPI) and virtual circuit indicator (VCI) are both carried together in the cell header, limiting ATM to a single level of tunneling.
[src:segment-routing/multiprotocol-label-switching] The biggest advantage that MPLS has over ATM is that it was designed from the start to be complementary to IP.
[src:segment-routing/multiprotocol-label-switching] Modern routers can support both MPLS and IP natively across a common interface allowing network operators great flexibility in network design and operation.
[src:segment-routing/multiprotocol-label-switching] ATM's incompatibilities with IP require complex adaptation, making it comparatively less suitable for today's predominantly IP networks.
[src:segment-routing/multiprotocol-label-switching] In practice, MPLS is mainly used to forward IP protocol data units (PDUs) and Virtual Private LAN Service (VPLS) Ethernet traffic.
[src:segment-routing/multiprotocol-label-switching] MPLS was originally proposed to allow high-performance traffic forwarding and traffic engineering in IP networks.
[src:segment-routing/multiprotocol-label-switching] However, it evolved in Generalized MPLS (GMPLS) to also allow the creation of LSPs in non-native IP networks, such as SONET/SDH networks and wavelength switched optical networks.
[src:segment-routing/segment-routing] Segment routing works either on top of a MPLS network or on an IPv6 network.
[src:segment-routing/segment-routing] In an MPLS network, segments are encoded as MPLS labels.
[src:segment-routing/segment-routing] Under IPv6, a new header called a Segment Routing Header (SRH) is used.
[src:segment-routing/segment-routing] Segments in a SRH are encoded in a list of IPv6 addresses.
[src:segment-routing/segment-routing] The *5f00::/16* prefix has been allocated for this purpose as part of an Internet-Draft.
